message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The patient presents with symptoms suggestive of a urinary tract infection, including dysuria, chills, and fever, and the physical exam shows pain in the right lower quadrant and flank area. The gynecologist's comment on ovarian cysts is not necessarily related to this current presentation. Ascending infection of the urinary tract is the most likely pathophysiology given these symptoms. The other options (cessation of venous drainage from the ovaries, inflammation of the appendix, vesicoureteral reflex) are less likely based on the patient's presentation.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The patient’s symptoms and physical examination findings suggest acute pyelonephritis, which is an ascending infection of the urinary tract. The history of ovarian cysts is not related to this presentation. Inflammation of the appendix typically presents with right lower quadrant pain but usually is associated with fever and leukocytosis. Vesicoureteral reflex, also known as vesicoureteral reflux, is a congenital condition that predisposes to urinary tract infections, but is not related to the patient’s presentation.
